Explaining Agile Roles (Scrum)​
Product Owner: Owns the product vision and prioritizes
the product backlog to maximize value delivered to
stakeholders.​

Scrum Master: Facilitates Scrum events, removes
impediments, and coaches the team on Agile principles.​

Developers: Cross-functional team members who design,
build, test, and deliver working product increments each
sprint.​

Clear role boundaries improve accountability,
collaboration, and delivery cadence (Schwaber &
Sutherland, 2020).​


Explaining Agile Phases (SDLC
in Agile)​
Planning: Backlog creation and refinement to
align work with business value.​

Design & Development: Iterative delivery of
small, usable increments.​

Testing: Continuous testing within each sprint
to maintain quality.​

Review & Retrospective: Inspect outcomes
and adapt processes for continuous
improvement (PMI, 2021).​


Describing the Waterfall Model​
Linear sequence of phases: Requirements →
Design → Build → Test → Deploy.​

Requirements are largely fixed upfront;
changes later in the process are costly.​

Stakeholder feedback often arrives late in the
lifecycle.​

Compared to Agile, Waterfall would have
delayed feedback and adaptation for SNHU
Travel (Atlassian, 2024).​


Choosing Waterfall or Agile
Choose Agile when requirements are evolving,
feedback is frequent, and rapid learning is
needed.​

Choose Waterfall when requirements are
stable, scope is well-defined, and
compliance/documentation is heavy.​

Agile supports faster learning cycles and value
delivery in dynamic environments (Rigby,
Sutherland, & Takeuchi, 2020).​
